The minister of environment, Dr. Mahmood Muhammad Abubakar has assured that Nigeria would provide purposeful leadership towards resolving ecological problems and recharge of Lake Chad, which is expected to improve the livelihoods of nationals residing within the areas as well as assist in addressing the environmental and security crisis threatening the region. He stated this in Abuja during the inauguration of the national implementation committee on afforestation. Abubakar recalled that President Muhammadu Buhari (PMB) had at the Seventy Fourth session of the United Nations General Assembly (74th UNGA), pledged that Nigeria would plant 25 million trees nationwide, which he said it’s in furtherance to demonstrating Nigeria’s commitment in addressing climate change including Nigeria’s commitment of four million hectares to the BONN challenge and fulfilling the Nationally Determined Contributions (NDC). According to him, “These collective efforts are further strengthened by successes recorded in the Green Bonds and on-going afforestation and reforestation efforts by various departments and agencies in the ministry to ensure a resilient future that mainstreams climate risks in decision making. Abubakar hinted that PMB’s commitment at the seventy fourth session of the United Nations General Assembly (UNGA) provided an opportunity for the inclusion of youths in decision making processes, saying that youths would be mobilized towards planting 25 million trees as part of Nigeria’s mitigation effort towards carbon sink. He promised that the ministry would provide the required leadership role in collaboration with federal ministries of education, youth and sports, women affairs, humanitarian affairs, disaster management and social development and national security adviser’s office. The minister noted that the implementation committee cuts across offices of the minister of environment, minister of state environment, permanent secretary, department of Forestry, department of Climate Change, National Agency for the Great Green Wall (NAGGW), National Parks Service (NPS), Private sector, Tropical Wood Exporters Association (TWEA) and among others. Abubakar appealed to all the committee members to be committed and be ready to sacrifice towards the successful planting of 25 million trees within the shortest possible time, just as he expressed optimism that with effective synergy by the relevant stakeholders that the target would be realizable. 